##Like the Eastern Steppe this is using OE's title history.
#OE only roughly goes up to ~1130 for most titles. After that I'll proceed to make things up to fill things out. I will make things up to fill in missing titles even before then as the AI will otherwise give the title to made up characters anyway so why not make use of the hundreds of unlanded historical characters and it also ensures the administrative divisions are properly set. This also helps with AI marriage as it gives more dynasties prestige
#Landed many Han in China during the later Yuan dates. One of the main causes for the fall of the Yuan was the exclusion of Han Chinese from government positions but having Mongols rule everything in China will never lead to any real rebellions unless I were to make events. A lot easier to just land actual characters to lead any possible rebellions

# Long list of titles to take proper advantage of insert_title_history so the dynasties aren't all called Yuan/Song/Tang since the games not able to do multiple insert_title_history in a single title as the last one will always overwrite the others. 'name =' is also whatever is the last one in the title history so it's pointless to have multiple entries of it in a title history but that name is preserved if you insert the title history. This does mean the Song and Tang have a second Empire title though which will always follow the primary heir and cannot de jure drift

		effect = {
			if = {
				limit = {
					exists = holder
					NOT = { has_dlc_feature = roads_to_power }
				}
				holder = {
					change_government = feudal_government
				}
			}
		}
		succession_laws = { male_only_law }
